"""Step 13: Scale the features

This standardizes your features so they all have mean ≈ 0 and standard deviation ≈ 1. This matters because your features are on very different scales (e.g., Age might range 20–80, while DiabetesPedigreeFunction ranges roughly 0–2.5) — without scaling, gradient descent struggles to converge properly.
Important detail (this fixes the bug from your original notebook):

sc.fit_transform(X_train) — calculates the mean/std from training data only, then scales it

sc.transform(X_test) — uses the same mean/std learned from training data to scale the test set (NOT fitting again on test data — that would leak information from the test set into your scaling)
"""

from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

sc = StandardScaler()

X_train_scaled = sc.fit_transform(X_train)
X_test_scaled = sc.transform(X_test)

